<xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LabelWrap*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LargeImageList\n  id: LargeImageList\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: LargeImageList\n  nameWithType: ListView.LargeImageList\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LargeImageList\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ImageList\"></xref> to use when displaying items as large icons in the control.\n  remarks: \"The LargeImageList property allows you to specify an <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> object that contains icons to use when displaying items with large icons (when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View%2A> property is set to <xref:System.Windows.Forms.View>). The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control can accept any graphics format that the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> control supports when displaying icons. The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control is not limited to .ico files. Once an <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> is assigned to the LargeImageList property, you can set the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ImageIndex%2A> property of each <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control to the index position of the appropriate image in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList>. The size of the icons for the LargeImageList is specified by the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList.ImageSize%2A>.  \\n  \\n Because only one index can be specified for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ImageIndex%2A?displayProperty=fullName> property, the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects specified in the LargeImageList and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SmallImageList%2A> properties should have the same index positions for the images to display. For example, if the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ImageIndex%2A> property of a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> is set to 0, the images to use for both small and large icons should be at the same index position in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects specified in the LargeImageList and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SmallImageList%2A> properties.  \\n  \\n> [!NOTE]\\n>  When the images are specified with keys, you still need to place small and large versions of the image at the same index location in their respective image lists. When switching between views, the index location of the image in one list is used to locate the image in the other list, regardless of the key value specified.  \\n  \\n To set the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> to use when displaying items with small icons (all view modes other than <xref:System.Windows.Forms.View>), use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SmallImageList%2A> property. If you want to use images to display item state, use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.StateImageList%2A> property.\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example creates a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control with three <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> objects specified and three <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ListViewSubItem> objects specified for each item. The example also creates <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ColumnHeader> objects to display the subitems in details view. Two <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects are also created in the code example to provide images for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> objects. These <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects are added to the LargeImageList and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SmallImageList%2A> properties. The example uses the following properties in creating the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control.  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LabelEdit%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.AllowColumnReorder%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.CheckBoxes%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.FullRowSelect%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.GridLines%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sorting%2A>  \\n  \\n This example requires that you have added the code to a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Form> and call the method created in the example from the constructor or another method on the form. The example also requires that images named `MySmallImage1`, `MySmallImage2`, `MyLargeImage1`, and `MyLargeImage2` are located in the root directory of drive C.  \\n  \\n [!code-cpp[ListViewExample#1](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_39_1.cpp)]\\n [!code-cs[ListViewExample#1](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_39_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[ListViewExample#1](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_39_1.vb)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public System.Windows.Forms.ImageList LargeImageList { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Windows.Forms.ImageList\n      description: An <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ImageList\"></xref> that contains the icons to use when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View*> property is set to <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.View\"></xref>. The default is <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_null\" name=\"null\" href=\"\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LargeImageList*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemSorter\n  id: ListViewItemSorter\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: ListViewItemSorter\n  nameWithType: ListView.ListViewItemSorter\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemSorter\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets the sorting comparer for the control.\n  remarks: \"The ListViewItemSorter property allows you to specify the object that performs the sorting of items in a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sort%2A> method is called or when items are added to the list. Note that items are not sorted automatically when their label text changes.  \\n  \\n The specified object must be an instance of a class that implements the <xref:System.Collections.IComparer> interface, which has a single method called <xref:System.Collections.Comparer.Compare%2A?displayProperty=fullName>.  \\n  \\n You can use this property to provide custom sorting, for example, when a column header is clicked in the details view. To do this, create a class that implements the <xref:System.Collections.IComparer> interface and provides a constructor that accepts the index of a column to sort by. You can then implement a handler for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ColumnClick> event that creates an instance of this class using the index of the clicked column. When you set the ListViewItemSorter property to the new instance, the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control is automatically sorted using the specified object. Subsequent calls to the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sort%2A> method use the same object.  \\n  \\n> [!NOTE]\\n>  When you set the value of the ListViewItemSorter property, the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sort%2A> method is called automatically.\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example creates a form that contains a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control that manually sorts items when a column in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control is clicked. The example defines a class called `ListViewItemComparer` that implements the <xref:System.Collections.IComparer?displayProperty=fullName> interface that performs the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> comparison. The example creates an instance of `ListViewItemComparer` and uses it to set the ListViewItemSorter property of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control. The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sort%2A> method call in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ColumnClick> event handler uses the methods defined in `ListViewItemComparer` to perform the sort of items, based on the column that is clicked.  \\n  \\n [!code-cpp[ListView.ColumnClick#1](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_31_1.cpp)]\\n [!code-cs[ListView.ColumnClick#1](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_31_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[ListView.ColumnClick#1](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_31_1.vb)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public System.Collections.IComparer ListViewItemSorter { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Collections.IComparer\n      description: An <xref:System.Collections.IComparer> that represents the sorting comparer for the control.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemSorter*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.MultiSelect\n  id: MultiSelect\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: MultiSelect\n  nameWithType: ListView.MultiSelect\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.MultiSelect\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets a value indicating whether multiple items can be selected.\n  remarks: \"When the MultiSelect property is set to `true`, multiple items can be selected in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control. To select multiple items, the user must hold down the CTRL key while clicking the items to select. Consecutive items can be selected by clicking the first item to select and then, while holding down the SHIFT key, clicking the last item to select. You can use the multiple selection feature to select multiple items in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control and perform an operation on all the items selected. For example, the user could select multiple items and then right-click a selected item to display a shortcut menu that displays a set of tasks that can be performed on the selected items.  \\n  \\n To determine which items are selected in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control, use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedItems%2A> property. The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedItems%2A> property allows you to access the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedListViewItemCollection> that contains a list of the selected items. If you want the index positions in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemCollection> instead of the items, you can use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndices%2A> property to access the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexCollection>.  \\n  \\n If you do not want to allow multiple selections in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView>, yet still want to offer the user a way for multiple items to be chosen, you can display check boxes by setting the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.CheckBoxes%2A> property to `true`.\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> that allows multiple items to be selected. The example demonstrates setting the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.HideSelection%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.HeaderStyle%2A> properties. To run this example, paste the following code into a form that contains a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> object named `ListView1` and a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.TextBox> named `TextBox1`. Call the `InitializeListView` method from the form's constructor or `Load` method.  \\n  \\n [!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_16_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_16_1.vb)]\\n [!code-cpp[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_16_1.cpp)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public bool MultiSelect { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Boolean\n      description: <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref> if multiple items in the control can be selected at one time; otherwise, <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_false\" name=\"false\" href=\"\"></xref>. The default is <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.MultiSelect*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.OnAfterLabelEdit(System.Windows.Forms.LabelEditEventArgs)\n  id: OnAfterLabelEdit(System.Windows.Forms.LabelEditEventArgs)\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: OnAfterLabelEdit(LabelEditEventArgs)\n  nameWithType: ListView.OnAfterLabelEdit(LabelEditEventArgs)\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.OnAfterLabelEdit(LabelEditEventArgs)\n  type: Method\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Raises the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ListView.AfterLabelEdit\"></xref> event.\n  remarks: \"Raising an event invokes the event handler through a delegate. For more information, see [Handling and Raising Events](~/add/includes/ajax-current-ext-md.md).  \\n  \\n The OnAfterLabelEdit method also allows derived classes to handle the event without attaching a delegate. This is the preferred technique for handling the event in a derived class.\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates how to use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.AfterLabelEdit> event to restrict a newly edited label to characters in the alphabet. The example uses the <xref:System.Text.ASCIIEncoding> class to obtain the ASCII character code of each character of the new label. If the character falls between the ASCII codes that represent numbers, the new label cannot be applied