ystem.InvalidOperationException\n    commentId: T:System.InvalidOperationException\n    description: The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.RetrieveVirtualItemEventArgs.Item*> property is not set to an item when the RetrieveVirtualItem event is handled.\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.RightToLeftLayout\n  id: RightToLeftLayout\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: RightToLeftLayout\n  nameWithType: ListView.RightToLeftLayout\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.RightToLeftLayout\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets a value indicating whether the control is laid out from right to left.\n  remarks: The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> property is for use with international applications where the language is read from right to left. If you set <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.RightToLeft> to true the control's contents and text will be laid out from right to left.\n  syntax:\n    content: public virtual bool RightToLeftLayout { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Boolean\n      description: <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref> to indicate the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ListView\"></xref> control is laid out from right to left; otherwise, <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_false\" name=\"false\" href=\"\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.RightToLeftLayout*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.RightToLeftLayoutChanged\n  id: RightToLeftLayoutChanged\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: RightToLeftLayoutChanged\n  nameWithType: ListView.RightToLeftLayoutChanged\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.RightToLeftLayoutChanged\n  type: Event\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Occurs when the value of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.RightToLeftLayout*> property changes.\n  remarks: For more information about handling events, see [Handling and Raising Events](~/add/includes/ajax-current-ext-md.md).\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates the use of this member. In the example, an event handler reports on the occurrence of the RightToLeftLayoutChanged event. This report helps you to learn when the event occurs and can assist you in debugging. To report on multiple events or on events that occur frequently, consider replacing <xref:System.Windows.Forms.MessageBox.Show%2A?displayProperty=fullName> with <xref:System.Console.WriteLine%2A?displayProperty=fullName> or appending the message to a multiline <xref:System.Windows.Forms.TextBox>.  \\n  \\n To run the example code, paste it into a project that contains an instance of type <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> named `ListView1`. Then ensure that the event handler is associated with the RightToLeftLayoutChanged event.  \\n  \\n [!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.EventExamples#462](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/e-system.windows.forms.l_14_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.EventExamples#462](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/e-system.windows.forms.l_14_1.vb)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public event EventHandler RightToLeftLayoutChanged;\n    return:\n      type: System.EventHandler\n      description: To be added.\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Scrollable\n  id: Scrollable\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: Scrollable\n  nameWithType: ListView.Scrollable\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Scrollable\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets a value indicating whether a scroll bar is added to the control when there is not enough room to display all items.\n  remarks: \"When this property is set to `true`, the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> displays a vertical scroll bar to use when the number of items exceeds the size of the client area of the control. You can use this property to ensure that the user can access all items that are available in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control.  \\n  \\n> [!NOTE]\\n>  In versions of the [!INCLUDE[dnprdnshort](~/add/includes/dnprdnshort-md.md)] prior to version 2.0, the column headers were not painted correctly when setting this property to `false` and resizing the control to make it larger. To work around this issue, set this property to `true` in a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Form.ResizeBegin> event handler and set it back to `false` in a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Form.ResizeEnd> event handler.\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public bool Scrollable { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Boolean\n      description: <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref> if scroll bars are added to the control when necessary to allow the user to see all the items; otherwise, <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_false\" name=\"false\" href=\"\"></xref>. The default is <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Scrollable*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SearchForVirtualItem\n  id: SearchForVirtualItem\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: SearchForVirtualItem\n  nameWithType: ListView.SearchForVirtualItem\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SearchForVirtualItem\n  type: Event\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Occurs when the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ListView\"></xref> is in virtual mode and a search is taking place.\n  remarks: \"This event occurs when a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> is in virtual mode and the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.FindNearestItem%2A> or <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.FindItemWithText%2A> method is called. When handling this event, you should calculate which item from the list of items supplied by the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Items%2A> property matches the search criteria and set the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.SearchForVirtualItemEventArgs.Index%2A?displayProperty=fullName> property to the index of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem>. If an item is not provided, <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.FindNearestItem%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.FindItemWithText%2A> will return `null`.  \\n  \\n For more information about handling events, see [Handling and Raising Events](~/add/includes/ajax-current-ext-md.md).\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates the use of this member. In the example, a search returns the nearest match to a specified integer in a list of the first ten thousand squares. This code example is part of a larger example provided for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.VirtualMode%2A> property.  \\n  \\n [!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListView.VirtualMode#4](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/e-system.windows.forms.l_1_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListView.VirtualMode#4](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/e-system.windows.forms.l_1_1.vb)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public event System.Windows.Forms.SearchForVirtualItemEventHandler SearchForVirtualItem;\n    return:\n      type: System.Windows.Forms.SearchForVirtualItemEventHandler\n      description: To be added.\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexChanged\n  id: SelectedIndexChanged\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: SelectedIndexChanged\n  nameWithType: ListView.SelectedIndexChanged\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexChanged\n  type: Event\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Occurs when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndices*> collection changes.\n  remarks: \"The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndices%2A> collection changes whenever the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.Selected%2A> property of a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> changes. The property change can occur programmatically or when the user selects an item or clears the selection of an item. When the user selects an item without pressing CTRL to perform a multiple selection, the control first clears the previous selection. In this case, this event occurs one time for each item that was previously selected and one time for the newly selected item.  \\n  \\n To determine which items are selected in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control, use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedItems%2A> property to access the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedListViewItemCollection>. You can create an event handler for this event to perform tasks whenever there is a change to the selected items in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control.  \\n  \\n For more information about handling events, see [Handling and Raising Events](~/add/includes/ajax-current-ext-md.md).\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates how to use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedItems%2A> property, SelectedIndexChanged event, <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.HeaderStyle%2A> members, and the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedListViewItemCollection> class. To run this example, paste the following code into a form that contains a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> object named `ListView1` and a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.TextBox> named `TextBox1`. Call the `InitializeListView` method from the form's constructor or `Load` method. This example requires that the event handler is correctly associated with the SelectedIndexChanged event  \\n  \\n [!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/e-system.windows.forms.l_13_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/e-system.windows.forms.l_13_1.vb)]\\n [!code-cpp[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/e-system.windows.forms.l_13_1.cpp)]  \\n[!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#2](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/e-system.windows.forms.l_13_2.cs)]\\n[!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#2](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/e-system.windows.forms.l_13_2.vb)]\\n[!code-cpp[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#2](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/e-system.windows.forms.l_13_2.cpp)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public event EventHandler SelectedIndexChanged;\n    return:\n      type: System.EventHandler\n      description: To be added.\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndices\n  id: SelectedIndices\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: SelectedIndices\n  nameWithType: ListView.SelectedIndices\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndices\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets the indexes of the selected items in the control.\n  remarks: \"The SelectedIndices property will not contain any indexes if the property is accessed before the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> handle is created, which typically occurs when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> is initially loaded for display in the form. You can check to see if the handle is created with the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.IsHandleCreated%2A> property. When the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.MultiSelect%2A> property is set to `true`, this property returns a collection containing the indexes of all items that are selected in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView>. For a single-selection <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView>, this property returns a collection containing a single element containing the index of the only selected item in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView>. For more information on the tasks that can be performed with the items in the collection, see <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexCollection>.  \\n  \\n If you want to obtain a collection of the items that are selected in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control, instead of the index positions of the items that are selected, use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedItems%2A> property.\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates using the SelectedIndices, <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexChanged>, and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.HeaderStyle%2A> members and the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexCollection> class. To run this example, paste the following code into a form that contains a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> object named `ListView1` and a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.TextBox> named `TextBox1`. Call the `InitializeListView` method from the form's constructor or `Load` method. This example requires the event handler is correctly associated with the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexChanged> event.  \\n  \\n [!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_22_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_22_1.vb)]\\n [!code-cpp[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_22_1.cpp)]  \\n[!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#3](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_22_2.cs)]\\n[!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#3](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_22_2.vb)]\\n[!code-cpp[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#3](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_22_2.cpp)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexCollection SelectedIndices { get; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexCollection\n      description: A <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexCollection> that contains the indexes of the selected items. If no items are currently selected, an empty <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexCollection> is returned.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndices*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedItems\n  id: SelectedItems\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: SelectedItems\n  nameWithType: ListView.SelectedItems\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedItems\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets the items that are selected in the control.\n  remarks: \"The SelectedItems property will not contain any items if the property is accessed before the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> handle is created, which typically occurs when <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> is initially loaded for display in the form. You can check to see if the handle is created with the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.IsHandleCreated%2A> property. When the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.MultiSelect%2A> property is set to `true`, this property returns a collection containing the items that are selected in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView>. For a single-selection <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView>, this property returns a collection containing the only selected item in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView>. For more information on the tasks that can be performed with the items in the collection, see <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedListViewItemCollection>.  \\n  \\n If you want to obtain a collection of the index positions within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemCollection> of the items that are selected in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control, instead of the items that are selected, use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndices%2A> property.\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates using the SelectedItems, <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexChanged> event, and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.HeaderStyle%2A> members and the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedListViewItemCollection> class. To run this example, paste the following code into a form that contains a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> object named `ListView1` and a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.TextBox> named `TextBox1`. Call the `InitializeListView` method from the form's constructor or `Load` method. This example requires the event handler is correctly associated with the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedIndexChanged> event  \\n  \\n [!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_21_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_21_1.vb)]\\n [!code-cpp[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#1](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_21_1.cpp)]  \\n[!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#2](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_21_2.cs)]\\n[!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#2](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_21_2.vb)]\\n[!code-cpp[System.Windows.Forms.ListView1#2](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_21_2.cpp)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedListViewItemCollection SelectedItems { get; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedListViewItemCollection\n      description: A <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedListViewItemCollection> that contains the items that are selected in the control. If no items are currently selected, an empty <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedListViewItemCollection> is returned.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SelectedItems*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ShowGroups\n  id: ShowGroups\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: ShowGroups\n  nameWithType: ListView.ShowGroups\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ShowGroups\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets a value indicating whether items are displayed in groups.\n  remarks: Any groups assigned to a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control appear whenever the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View%2A> property is set to a value other than <xref:System.Windows.Forms.View>. The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> grouping feature lets you create visual groups of logically related <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> items on Windows XP and Windows Server 2003. To enable this feature, your application must call the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Application.EnableVisualStyles%2A?displayProperty=fullName> method. For more information, see the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Groups%2A> property.\n  syntax:\n    content: public bool ShowGroups { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Boolean\n      description: <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref> to display items in groups; otherwise, <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_false\" name=\"false\" href=\"\"></xref>. The default value is <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ShowGroups*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ShowItemToolTips\n  id: ShowItemToolTips\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: ShowItemToolTips\n  nameWithType: ListView.ShowItemToolTips\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ShowItemToolTips\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets a value indicating whether ToolTips are shown for the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem\"></xref> objects contained in the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ListView\"></xref>.\n  remarks: If the ShowItemToolTips property is set to `true`, any <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> that has a ToolTip will display it; otherwise, nothing is displayed.\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates how to use the ShowItemToolTips and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ToolTipText%2A?displayProperty=fullName> properties. To run this example, paste the code into a Windows Form and call `InitializeItemsWithToolTips` from the form's constructor or <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Form.Load> event handler.  \\n  \\n [!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItemWhidbeyMembers#4](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_51_1.vb)]\\n [!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItemWhidbeyMembers#4](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_51_1.cs)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public bool ShowItemToolTips { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Boolean\n      description: <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref> if <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem\"></xref> ToolTips should be shown; otherwise, <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_false\" name=\"false\" href=\"\"></xref>. The default is <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_true\" name=\"true\" href=\"\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ShowItemToolTips*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SmallImageList\n  id: SmallImageList\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: SmallImageList\n  nameWithType: ListView.SmallImageList\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SmallImageList\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ImageList\"></xref> to use when displaying items as small icons in the control.\n  remarks: \"The SmallImageList property allows you to specify an <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> object that contains icons to use when displaying items with small icons (when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View%2A> property is set to any value other than <xref:System.Windows.Forms.View>). The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control can accept any graphics format that the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> control supports when displaying icons. The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control is not limited to .ico files. Once an <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> is assigned to the SmallImageList property, you can set the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ImageIndex%2A> property of each <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control to the index position of the appropriate image in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList>. The size of the icons for the SmallImageList is specified by the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList.ImageSize%2A> property.  \\n  \\n Because only one index can be specified for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ImageIndex%2A?displayProperty=fullName> property, the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects specified in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LargeImageList%2A> and SmallImageList properties should have the same index positions for the images to display. For example, if the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ImageIndex%2A> property of a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> is set to 0, the images to use for both small and large icons should be at the same index position in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects specified in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LargeImageList%2A> and SmallImageList properties.  \\n  \\n> [!NOTE]\\n>  When the images are specified with keys, you still need to place small and large versions of the image at the same index location in their respective image lists. When switching between views, the index location of the image in one list is used to locate the image in the other list, regardless of the key value specified.  \\n  \\n To set the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> to use when displaying items with large icons (when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View%2A> property is set to <xref:System.Windows.Forms.View>), use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LargeImageList%2A> property. If you want to use images to display item state, use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.StateImageList%2A> property.\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example creates a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control with three <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> objects specified and three <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ListViewSubItem> objects specified for each item. The example also creates <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ColumnHeader> objects to display the subitems in details view. Two <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects are also created in the code example to provide images for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> objects. These <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects are added to the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LargeImageList%2A> and SmallImageList properties. The example uses the following properties in creating the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control.  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LabelEdit%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.AllowColumnReorder%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.CheckBoxes%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.FullRowSelect%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.GridLines%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sorting%2A>  \\n  \\n This example requires that you have added the code to a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Form> and call the method created in the example from the constructor or another method on the form. The example also requires that images named `MySmallImage1`, `MySmallImage2`, `MyLargeImage1`, and `MyLargeImage2` are located in the root directory of drive C.  \\n  \\n [!code-cpp[ListViewExample#1](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_5_1.cpp)]\\n [!code-cs[ListViewExample#1](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_5_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[ListViewExample#1](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_5_1.vb)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public System.Windows.Forms.ImageList SmallImageList { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Windows.Forms.ImageList\n      description: An <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ImageList\"></xref> that contains the icons to use when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View*> property is set to <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.View\"></xref>. The default is <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_null\" name=\"null\" href=\"\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SmallImageList*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sort\n  id: Sort\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: Sort()\n  nameWithType: ListView.Sort()\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sort()\n  type: Method\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Sorts the items of the list view.\n  remarks: \"Typically items are sorted using the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sorting%2A> property, which sorts items based on the item text. To customize the sort order, you must write a class that implements the <xref:System.Collections.IComparer> interface and set the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemSorter%2A> property to an object of that class. This is useful, for example, when you want to sort items by subitem text. For more information on performing manual sorting of items, see the example for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemSorter%2A> property.  \\n  \\n If the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sorting%2A?displayProperty=fullName> property is set to a value other than <xref:System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder?displayProperty=fullName> or if the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemSorter%2A> property is set, the list is sorted automatically when items are added. Items are not sorted automatically when the label text changes.\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public void Sort ();\n    parameters: []\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sort*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sorting\n  id: Sorting\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: Sorting\n  nameWithType: ListView.Sorting\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sorting\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets the sort order for items in the control.\n  remarks: \"The Sorting property allows you to specify whether or not items are sorted in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control. By default, no sorting is performed. When the Sorting property is set to <xref:System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder> or <xref:System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder>, the items in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> are sorted automatically in ascending alphabetical order (when the property is set to <xref:System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder>) or descending alphabetical order (when the property is set to <xref:System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder>). You can use this property to automatically sort items that are displayed in your <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control to make it easier for users to find items when a large number of items are available.  \\n  \\n If you want to perform your own item sorting instead of using the Sorting property, use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemSorter%2A> property in combination with the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sort%2A> method.  \\n  \\n If the Sorting property is set to a value other than <xref:System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder?displayProperty=fullName> or if the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ListViewItemSorter%2A> property is set, the list is sorted automatically when items is added. Items are not sorted automatically when the label text changes.\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example creates a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control with three <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> objects specified and three <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ListViewSubItem> objects specified for each item. The example also creates <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ColumnHeader> objects to display the subitems in details view. Two <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects are also created in the code example to provide images for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> objects. These <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> objects are added to the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LargeImageList%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.SmallImageList%2A> properties. The example uses the following properties in creating the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control.  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.LabelEdit%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.AllowColumnReorder%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.CheckBoxes%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.FullRowSelect%2A>  \\n  \\n-   <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.GridLines%2A>  \\n  \\n-   Sorting  \\n  \\n This example requires that you have added the code to a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Form> and call the method created in the example from the constructor or another method on the form. The example also requires that images named `MySmallImage1`, `MySmallImage2`, `MyLargeImage1`, and `MyLargeImage2` are located in the root directory of drive C.  \\n  \\n [!code-cpp[ListViewExample#1](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_19_1.cpp)]\\n [!code-cs[ListViewExample#1](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_19_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[ListViewExample#1](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_19_1.vb)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder Sorting { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder\n      description: One of the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder\"></xref> values. The default is <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Sorting*\n  exceptions:\n  - type: System.ComponentModel.InvalidEnumArgumentException\n    commentId: T:System.ComponentModel.InvalidEnumArgumentException\n    description: The value specified is not one of the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.SortOrder\"></xref> values.\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.StateImageList\n  id: StateImageList\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: StateImageList\n  nameWithType: ListView.StateImageList\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.StateImageList\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ImageList\"></xref> associated with application-defined states in the control.\n  remarks: \"The StateImageList property allows you to specify an <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> that contains images to use to represent an application-specific state of an item in a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control. State images are displayed to the left of an icon for the item. You can use state images, such as checked and unchecked check boxes, to indicate application-defined item states. State images are visible in all views of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control.  \\n  \\n If an <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> is specified in the StateImageList property and the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.CheckBoxes%2A> property is set to `true`, the images at index positions 0 and 1 in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> are displayed instead of the check box. The image at index position 0 is displayed instead of the unchecked check box, and the image at index position 1 is displayed instead of the checked check box.\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public System.Windows.Forms.ImageList StateImageList { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Windows.Forms.ImageList\n      description: An <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ImageList\"></xref> that contains a set of state images that can be used to indicate an application-defined state of an item. The default is <xref uid=\"langword_csharp_null\" name=\"null\" href=\"\"></xref>.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.StateImageList*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Text\n  id: Text\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: Text\n  nameWithType: ListView.Text\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Text\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: This property is not relevant for this class.\n  remarks: This property is not relevant for this class.\n  syntax:\n    content: public override string Text { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.String\n      description: The text to display in the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ListView\"></xref> control.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Text*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.TextChanged\n  id: TextChanged\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: TextChanged\n  nameWithType: ListView.TextChanged\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.TextChanged\n  type: Event\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Occurs when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Text*> property changes.\n  syntax:\n    content: public event EventHandler TextChanged;\n    return:\n      type: System.EventHandler\n      description: To be added.\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.TileSize\n  id: TileSize\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: TileSize\n  nameWithType: ListView.TileSize\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.TileSize\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets the size of the tiles shown in tile view.\n  remarks: This property controls the size of tiles when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View%2A> property is set to <xref:System.Windows.Forms.View?displayProperty=fullName>. Setting this property is useful to prevent line-wrapping when subitem text is too long to be displayed on a single line.\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates how to use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> tiling feature. In the example, the tile view displays items that represent books. Each item is shown as a tile containing an icon of a book, the title, the author, and the publication year. For the example code to work, you must include an icon file named Book.ico in the same directory as the example. To see the tile view without icons, comment out the lines relating to the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ImageList> object.  \\n  \\n [!code-cpp[System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Tiling#1](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_0_1.cpp)]\\n [!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Tiling#1](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_0_1.cs)]\\n [!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Tiling#1](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_0_1.vb)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public System.Drawing.Size TileSize { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Drawing.Size\n      description: A <xref href=\"System.Drawing.Size\"></xref> that contains the new tile size.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.TileSize*\n  exceptions: []\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.TopItem\n  id: TopItem\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: TopItem\n  nameWithType: ListView.TopItem\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.TopItem\n  type: Property\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Gets or sets the first visible item in the control.\n  remarks: \"Initially, the item with the index position of zero (0) is at the top of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control. If the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control contents are scrolled, a different item can be at the top of the control. You can use this property to indicate or determine which item is visible at the top of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control. The value of the TopItem property will not always persist, depending on where the desired top item is in the list view.  \\n  \\n The number of items visible in a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView> control at any time depends on the height of the list view and the size of the items it contains. If the items exceed the height of the list view, the items will continue onto multiple pages, which the user can scroll through. If you set the TopItem property to an item in the last page of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView>, the item will automatically be scrolled into view; however, TopItem will be set to the actual top item of the last page.  \\n  \\n To ensure that a specific item is in the visible region of the control (but not necessarily in the top position), use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.EnsureVisible%2A> method.  \\n  \\n> [!NOTE]\\n>  Setting this property has no effect when the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.Scrollable%2A> property value is `false`.  \\n>   \\n>  Setting this property is not supported in versions of the [!INCLUDE[dnprdnshort](~/add/includes/dnprdnshort-md.md)] prior to version 2.0.\"\n  example:\n  - \"The following code example demonstrates resetting the style of a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem> object's subitems through the use of the TopItem property and the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem.ListViewSubItem.ResetStyle%2A?displayProperty=fullName> method. To run the example, paste the following code into a form containing a button named `Button1` and call the `InitializeListView` method in the form's constructor or <xref:System.Windows.Forms.Form.Load> event handler.  \\n  \\n [!code-cs[System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItemStyle#2](~/add/codesnippet/csharp/p-system.windows.forms.l_77_1.cs)]\\n [!code-cpp[System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItemStyle#2](~/add/codesnippet/cpp/p-system.windows.forms.l_77_1.cpp)]\\n [!code-vb[System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItemStyle#2](~/add/codesnippet/visualbasic/p-system.windows.forms.l_77_1.vb)]\"\n  syntax:\n    content: public System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem TopItem { get; set; }\n    return:\n      type: System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem\n      description: A <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ListViewItem\"></xref> that represents the first visible item in the control.\n  overload: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.TopItem*\n  exceptions:\n  - type: System.InvalidOperationException\n    commentId: T:System.InvalidOperationException\n    description: The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListView.View*> property is set to <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.View\"></xref>,  <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.View\"></xref>, or <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.View\"></xref>.\n  platform:\n  - net462\n- uid: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ToString\n  id: ToString\n  parent: System.Windows.Forms.ListView\n  langs:\n  - csharp\n  name: ToString()\n  nameWithType: ListView.ToString()\n  fullName: System.Windows.Forms.ListView.ToString()\n  type: Method\n  assemblies:\n  - System.Windows.Forms\n  namespace: System.Windows.Forms\n  summary: Returns a string representation of the <xref href=\"System.Windows.Forms.ListView\"></xref> control.\n  syntax:\n    content: public override string ToString ();\n    parameter